00:36.500 --> 00:38.200
And here are your hosts.

00:42.780 --> 00:50.680
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Harry Harrison has made a name for himself
in science fiction in many areas. He's noted for his novels, short stories, and

00:50.680 --> 00:57.580
the anthologies he's edited. One of Harrison's notable contributions is the
popularization of so-called adventure science fiction. It's typified by the

00:57.580 --> 01:05.180
trilogy whose volumes are aptly named Death World 1, Death World 2, and Death
World 3. Harrison told us how this particular brand of science fiction

01:05.180 --> 01:14.440
originated with the writing of Death World 1. You mentioned the fact that it's
adventure science fiction. Well, don't laugh, but at that time in science

01:14.440 --> 01:23.240
fiction, which was Campbell, which was Analog, if you were a true blue reader,
well, you read Startling Stories and Thrilling Wonder, because you had to wait

01:23.240 --> 01:31.220
another three weeks for the next issue of Astounding. That's where the action
was. And he had a very cerebral. He had a whole novel of people talking to each

01:31.220 --> 01:40.000
other, nothing moving at all, no action. And I wanted to do a book that had
action part of the plot. I mean, that's sort of stupid to say now, with all the

01:40.000 --> 01:50.640
guns blowing heads away. I mean, that whole gore school and the whole sword and
sorcery, sword and butchery. I mean, action galore for no reason at all. But in

01:50.640 --> 01:59.060
those days, it was getting dim, I thought. So I worked out, but I didn't want to
do an action plot for action, say. So I'm a great backplotter. In the sense, I

01:59.060 --> 02:05.100
find a reason to do a book and then fit a book to the reason. And the reason I
wanted to have the action, I wanted to have a realistic, so I thought it was

02:05.100 --> 02:05.440
Superman.

02:08.860 --> 02:17.180
And in this book, you find, if you look at it closely, it's done in two or three
levels. The action plots are surface. But there, below that, is the idea of

02:17.180 --> 02:25.560
Superman that Nietzsche talked about and that Superman magazine talks about. And
I'm very much against Superman, physical Superman. And if you look in the book,

02:25.620 --> 02:34.180
you'll see that if you are so brutalized to be physically a Superman, your
intellectual content is zero. And I said that in a number of different ways. And

02:34.180 --> 02:41.320
I'm very much against militarism. And that's sitting there in a number of
different ways. All of it couched in an adventure plot. And it's up to the

02:41.320 --> 02:49.220
reader to read it whichever way he wants. And he'll find a good adventure plot
if he wants. He'll find even more about it. I remember when I first published

02:49.220 --> 02:59.480
it, a reader in England came up to me. And I was looking for a great return from
literate Englishmen about heavily intellectual content. And he said, oh, Harry,

02:59.740 --> 03:07.300
I read that book. I told my friends to read it. Oh, I like it. You did? What did
you tell me? He said, oh, really? I said, it's all about guns.

03:18.360 --> 03:26.440
The protagonist of Death World 1 is Jason dinAlt. Harrison liked him so much
that he had to write two more installments. The Death World 2 and 3 came out by

03:26.440 --> 03:35.820
happenstance. It's just that the character was successful. I wanted to write
another adventure-style book. And I realized after I wrote it, I left the ending

03:35.820 --> 03:43.040
open. You had to get these people off that planet. A certain part of them had to
leave. They're just good for killing things. You start thinking about it. And

03:43.040 --> 03:50.700
they're friends with his. And he's a weak man personally. And he has, like I
say, he supplies a part that they don't supply. They have the big bodies and the

03:50.700 --> 03:58.080
tiny, poignant heads. He's a weakling in their terms, but he's a man of
intelligence. So therefore, I said, gee, well, if I went to another planet, he

03:58.080 --> 04:05.980
had a problem. He'd have to go along and organize it. And then the plot
developed. I did that once more. And that was the end of it, as far as I was

04:05.980 --> 04:13.880
concerned. People asked for another Death World. No, I run that particular plot
device. Well, I was pinned into it. And it worked three times. It worked pretty

04:13.880 --> 04:25.060
well. Harrison told us his books usually have philosophical content. Death World
2, for instance. Okay, Death World 2, you may think it's about going off and

04:25.060 --> 04:34.560
blowing things up and killing things and rushing around. It really is. The
entire book is about the difference in meaning. Between ethics and ethos. And

04:34.560 --> 04:40.840
that's what it's about. I keep repeating over and over through that thing. And a
lot of guns go off and a lot of good things happen. You learn a bit of

04:40.840 --> 04:50.940
Esperanto. But also, what science fiction can do, it's a book that takes the
study of a philosophical question or a problem of meaning of meaning. We'll have

04:50.940 --> 04:52.420
more with Harry Harrison on our next show.

04:59.600 --> 05:07.340
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show. A production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:07.340 --> 05:14.920
Odessa, Texas. 

