07:02.500 --> 07:09.300
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. One of science fiction writer Harry
Harrison's most unforgettable characters is Slippery Jim diGriz, the

07:09.300 --> 07:17.760
stainless steel rat. The stainless steel rat's adventure span five novels so
far. We asked Harrison where he got the concept of a stainless steel rat. I

07:17.760 --> 07:26.500
remember the basic idea. It was just that, as the old rat says, that we have,
you know, flesh and blood rats in wooden buildings. We'll have stainless steel

07:26.500 --> 07:35.300
rats in concrete ones. Then Harrison went on to tell us a bit about the first
novel in the series, The Stainless Steel Rat, and how the idea then grew. It's

07:35.300 --> 07:46.120
basically a very old idea of the villain as hero. Turn the world on his head.
This is where you have in The Saint, who tends to pontificate a little bit too

07:46.120 --> 07:59.120
much. It's where you have Rupert of Hentzau in that Prisoner of Zenda. We all
love him better than we do. The goody-goodies do their job. It is, if you'll

07:59.120 --> 08:05.320
pardon the expression, my dear friend Kingsley Amis had a picaresque novel. Now,
don't be ashamed if you don't understand what that means. I said, thanks,

08:05.520 --> 08:14.640
Kingsley. I ran off to a dictionary. The picaresque novel is just that. The hero
as villain, villain as hero. And when I realized that what I was doing, that I'd

08:14.640 --> 08:23.100
come onto a formula, and I was trying to get humor into it as well. There was no
humor in science fiction. It's nothing that I was doing. Anyone else alive? A

08:23.100 --> 08:33.560
character developed as it went along, and I get clues back from readers about
it. And an English reader told me he likes to read the thing because the hero

08:33.560 --> 08:42.100
does all the things he wished he could do against society and gets away with it.
You know, everyone hates bureaucracy. And I said, by God, you're right. I

08:42.100 --> 08:48.620
thought about it in the very next rat book. The first chapter has nothing to do
with the rest of the book if you look at it. It's just something happens to his

08:48.620 --> 08:55.840
dear wife, Angelina, and the enemy has her, and he goes off. The enemy is the
Internal Review Service, the old IRS man, you know. He goes and burns out all

08:55.840 --> 09:02.000
the income tax records for the whole planet, cheering everybody up, you know.
And the story begins. But that's something we all wish could happen tomorrow,

09:02.100 --> 09:09.800
except for the people who work for the IRS. The stainless steel rat novels form
a humorous adventure series. We ask Harrison what place humor has in science

09:09.800 --> 09:21.880
fiction. Very little. It could have a bigger one. And the answer is a very
mechanical one. Editors, for the most part, are dummies. And even the few bright

09:21.880 --> 09:30.420
ones have their own particular taste in humor. That is a matter of taste. You
bring an adventure novel in, an editor will say, Yeah, well, Harry's done

09:30.420 --> 09:36.900
better, but it moves along, people are killed, I'll buy it. Bring a love story
in, oh, well, your girl gets kissed, you know, it's a little boring, but I'll

09:36.900 --> 09:46.440
buy it. You bring in a humor novel, he doesn't laugh. He does not buy it. And
editors, if they laugh, I've heard them say, One of them is a rejecter, it was

09:46.440 --> 09:54.220
too funny. They're afraid the readers won't laugh. So the only way you can sell
humor is have a reputation as a humor writer. And how do you get a humor writer?

09:54.320 --> 10:01.420
You've got to sell a book, but you can't sell it. It's a Catch-22 thing. And I
snuck it in The Stainless Street Rat. I would make each one a little bit funnier

10:01.420 --> 10:08.720
than the one before. And eventually, the editor was laughing, readers were
laughing, hurrah, I'm a humor writer. Harrison's early characters, Jason dinAlt

10:08.720 --> 10:16.820
and Slippery Jim diGriz, are strong characters. But Harrison told us science
fiction is really based on ideas, not characters. Science fiction is not a

10:16.820 --> 10:25.560
character-based form of fiction. You can have three-dimensional characters in
science fiction. But the idea comes first. It's an idea fiction. To form a

10:25.560 --> 10:34.660
fiction where you can have the idea as hero, anything that has that, isn't what
you call three-dimensional, have the idea for a character who would do these

10:34.660 --> 10:44.960
things. Which means far too often in science fiction, you'll get two-dimensional
characters who just act the assigned role of the plot, given by the author. And

10:44.960 --> 10:53.880
we don't mind reading that. We really want to read about the action. To make
good science fiction viable, interesting, fun science fiction, when you have to

10:53.880 --> 11:01.440
assign the character the role, you must build his character as a character.
That's where the art comes. There are two things in all kinds of fiction. The

11:01.440 --> 11:09.480
craft of science fiction, constructing your plot. The art of science fiction is
making your characters three-dimensional. Which is true for any character I

11:09.480 --> 11:18.780
write. But very rarely in science fiction do you have character-based fiction.
If you have, it's usually not science fiction. More with Harry Harrison on our

11:18.780 --> 11:19.280
next show.

11:26.700 --> 11:34.620
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

11:34.620 --> 11:35.380
Odessa, Texas.

