12:58.500 --> 13:06.240
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Perhaps science fiction author Harry
Harrison's single most famous novel is Bill, the Galactic Hero. The protagonist

13:06.240 --> 13:13.580
is Bill, a hayseed from the farm who gets Shanghai'd into the Empire Space Corps
to fight the evil Chingers. Bill, the Galactic Hero is a spoof of war,

13:13.760 --> 13:23.320
bureaucracy, and the pulps, among other things. Here, Harrison comments on some
of the influences which helped inspire the novel. Bill, the Galactic Hero, there

13:23.320 --> 13:32.920
again, he was assigned a role. He was, you know, a good soldier, Shveik. He's
the guy who gets it in the neck all the time, and happened to be a science

13:32.920 --> 13:43.960
fiction army. And I think it just makes it explode in me. Having been in the
army and seated here in the heart of the military, I'm an enlisted man. I have

13:43.960 --> 13:50.340
the highest rank in the army, that of sergeant. You have to get the general
before you get anything higher than that. Second lieutenant, you know, grubs to

13:50.340 --> 14:00.040
be walked on. And it's a whole different attitude. And the officers like the
military. They like to tell people what to do. And usually what they tell them

14:00.040 --> 14:09.480
to do is not for the good of the people they're talking to. They should get
killed for it. But the enlisted men want to stay alive. As Yossarian said in

14:09.480 --> 14:17.920
Catch-22, they're trying to kill me. He didn't mean the enemy. He meant the army
he was in. And knowing all this, reading all this, Catch-22 came out. I was a

14:17.920 --> 14:30.260
great fan of Candide. And when I saw Catch-22, what he did, Heller did, he
showed that there's something so awful that you have to laugh at them to

14:30.260 --> 14:37.180
understand them. If you're doing a military novel, you say blood, blood, death,
intestines from the trees. By the 20th time you hang the intestines from the

14:37.180 --> 14:43.940
trees, you're tired of looking at them. They look like spaghetti after a while.
Repetition of horror doesn't make horror. And that's all you can do. The army is

14:43.940 --> 14:47.800
utterly horrible, boring, and wasteful. The military life is boring and
wasteful.

14:50.640 --> 15:02.120
And in there, I parodied a few other novels just for fun of it. But the thing
that goes right through it is understanding the military. Years later I

15:02.120 --> 15:11.600
discovered that. I had a Korean War veteran come up to me. He was a combat
Marine. He wanted to have his face all shot away. And I said, Yeah, huh, huh? I

15:11.600 --> 15:19.760
said, Yes, yeah. He said, You wrote Bill, the Galactic Hero? I said, Yes, looking
for a chair to hide behind. He said, I've got a copy of every edition of that

15:19.760 --> 15:31.780
book. I carry it through to combat, you know. And that tells a story. Another
guy, same thing, John Paul. He was a real Green Beret. He had a bangle. He

15:31.780 --> 15:39.960
worked with the Montagnards. Not like John Wayne with a fake one. You know, he
was up there. And he killed things. He had great killing. And, uh, it was like,

15:40.080 --> 15:47.960
you know, Napoleon's troops carried a Marshall's baton in their pack. He carried
a copy of Bill, the Galactic Hero. All through the Korean War, up there, killing gooks

15:47.960 --> 15:57.120
and everything. And he used to get his rookies in. He'd read them a chapter
every night. Whether they liked it or no. He'd break them in half, you know. So,

15:57.120 --> 16:05.900
I really feel that it's humor and it's parody and it's a lot of fun. But it
tells you something about the military condition that is absolutely dead true.

16:11.960 --> 16:21.600
In fact, Harrison believes his version of war, as depicted in Bill, the Galactic
Hero, comes closer to reality than do the more serious novels of others. The pro

16:21.600 --> 16:28.860
-military novel is like Starship Troopers, you know, where everyone's being kind
to each other. I mean, if, uh, in fact, I saw Norman Spinrad put it in an

16:28.860 --> 16:38.280
article the other week, uh, as Harry Harrison said, it looked like it's always
Bobby or Buddy Week. And this was, um, we said in the Army, in, a novel whose

16:38.280 --> 16:46.280
name I shall not mention, the guy in a heavy space armor is going down and all
friends come to rescue him, you know. And, uh, in Bill, the guy goes in a swamp

16:46.280 --> 16:53.820
and the soldiers are marching by, he says, help me, help me, and they walk on
by, he says, what is this? Bob, your Buddy Week! And they say, it's always Bob,

16:53.980 --> 17:05.200
your Buddy Week! And that's what you should say in the Army, you know. I mean,
uh, uh, it always is. It's every man for himself. Normally, normally. You expect

17:05.200 --> 17:10.180
to get it put in and broken off, and usually it does. We'll have more with Harry
Harrison on our next show.

