18:47.820 --> 18:54.820
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Harry Harrison is noted for his humorous
science fiction works as well as his adventure science fiction. Right. But

18:54.820 --> 19:02.640
Harrison wrote the very serious novel, Make Room, Make Room, which portrays a
grim, near-future earth plagued with overpopulation. Some may be more familiar

19:02.640 --> 19:10.520
with the movie loosely based on this novel, Soylent Green. Harrison's concern
for overpopulation inspired his writing, Make Room, Make Room. His primary

19:10.520 --> 19:18.300
concern while writing was to avoid both lecturing and preaching. And I felt very
serious about population. At that time, I wrote the book. There were no

19:18.300 --> 19:25.420
fictional works on population. There were no, these popular nonfiction books
hadn't come out. The world was completely unaware where we were going. And I

19:25.420 --> 19:31.380
could see it. I lived in Mexico and watched what was happening. You read the
learned journals. They told you about it. So I wanted to do a propaganda work

19:31.380 --> 19:42.160
that was disguised as not being propaganda. And so I set it in the year 1999 New
York. Makes a millennial novel. Brings a lot of overtones, you know, the

19:42.160 --> 19:50.900
millennium, coming of Christ, and that sort of thing. And I didn't want to
lecture. So I very simply started a book, put the characters in the world, went

19:50.900 --> 20:01.420
along for almost a fifth of the book, and got everyone involved before someone
turned to one character, the older character. How did the world get this way? At

20:01.420 --> 20:07.720
this point, I felt the reader was trapped enough to take one page of lecture.
And I sent the book in my head and said, Harry, they're trapped enough to take

20:07.720 --> 20:16.620
four pages of lecture. So I just put in four pages, a copy, about a thousand
words, two pages in the book, telling you how it worked out that way. So my one

20:16.620 --> 20:24.700
little lecture right there, having done that little lecture, the book was, in a
sense, a work of propaganda and art. If you're better at the art, the better at

20:24.700 --> 20:33.740
the propaganda. 1984 is propaganda. On the beach is propaganda. They're both
art. You get the message. And that was it. And after that, I worked around the

20:33.740 --> 20:41.580
point. And if you were alive and warm, you understood it. And the readers did.
Harrison worked hard to involve the reader by painting a picture of the future

20:41.580 --> 20:50.240
using indirect descriptions rather than simply telling the reader the situation
directly. I think, having worked as an artist for a number of years, I see in my

20:50.240 --> 20:55.440
mind when I'm writing, I have a stage of people walking around and I see what's
in the background, the foreground. I hear the waves splashing and see them

20:55.440 --> 20:55.820
splashing.

20:58.720 --> 21:11.580
And as always in writing, you should never tell you should show. And good
writing is hard work. It should be transparent. The reader should not see how

21:11.580 --> 21:18.820
you got the effect. And one of the best ways, of course, it's hard to do is
never say. The world is full of a lot of people. Never say you're short of

21:18.820 --> 21:28.080
water. Show them on a line to get water out of a standpipe. And then you know
you're short of water and dramatize their need for the water. And this is where

21:28.080 --> 21:28.900
your art comes in,

21:32.220 --> 21:40.260
which far too often, if the writer cannot do that, then he does not succeed on
that level. People read his book for fun, but if you can get the reader

21:40.260 --> 21:48.000
emotionally involved, get him trapped into the book, and he comes out of the end
maybe not agreeing with you, but at least he knows what you said. He will be

21:48.000 --> 21:53.740
thinking about it. And I had one note. One girl read that book in New York. She
said, if I thought the world would be like that, I'd commit suicide. I said,

21:53.820 --> 22:01.880
don't, don't. The mere act of thinking that means you're going to vote right and
work so this world will not appear. That's a science fiction admonishing finger

22:01.880 --> 22:10.640
again, saying shape up or ship out. If you don't do this, you'll get that. Make
Room, Make Room is also a mystery novel. Harrison chose this vehicle because it

22:10.640 --> 22:20.320
allowed him to show society from bottom to top. All of science fiction, for the
most part, is based on detective plot. The mystery will be solved. Even if

22:20.320 --> 22:27.000
they're not called, like Hal Clements' Needle, not officially a mystery, you
want to find how you got that way. Will they solve the problem? Will they all

22:27.000 --> 22:36.580
live? Will they get all this world? Will they do it? That was a deliberate bit
of my plot, a plot device of mine, that I wanted to show society from the lowest

22:36.580 --> 22:44.080
levels to the high. I wanted to show how everybody lived in that world. So I
used a very simple device of having a detective as protagonist. A very simple

22:44.080 --> 22:51.560
story. And we all knew at the beginning who did the murder. We knew what was
going to happen. And it was not important, but it was a device to move the story

22:51.560 --> 22:59.540
along. And like most crimes in New York, 90% aren't solved. It's just by chance
that they are. This was a way of getting you into the various levels of the

22:59.540 --> 23:03.200
stratus of society. On our next show, we'll talk about Soylent Green.

