This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

24:34.200 --> 24:35.980
And here are your hosts.

24:40.320 --> 24:48.820
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Make Room, Make Room. Harry Harrison's grim
novel of an overpopulated near-future New York was the basis for the movie

24:48.820 --> 24:56.380
Soylent Green. This movie made its appearance in the early 1970s, and it starred
Charlton Heston and Edward G. Robinson. One of the movie's claims to fame is

24:56.380 --> 25:03.420
that it was the last motion picture Edward G. Robinson played in. We spoke with
Harrison about the transformation of the novel to the movie, and we were

25:03.420 --> 25:09.660
particularly interested how the movie came to be plotted around cannibalism,
whereas this was never mentioned in the novel. Harrison told us an interesting

25:09.660 --> 25:19.040
story which vividly shows how things apparently work in Hollywood. The first
time I heard about the fact they wanted to make a film out of this book was when

25:19.040 --> 25:28.120
I was approached for a contract, and I signed it. And then it turned out the
firm that bought it was a front for MGM, and they sold MGM for $1. They hate to

25:28.120 --> 25:35.580
pay the writer a decent fee. For some reason, they pay everyone else. They don't
like to pay writers in Hollywood. And it turned out that the producer, Walter

25:35.580 --> 25:46.440
Seltzer, and the lead actor, Chuck Heston, had been trying to sell to MGM for
five years, and they couldn't sell. MGM thought that overpopulation wasn't

25:46.440 --> 25:55.680
important enough to do a film on. So they then got a moronic screenwriter who
put in cannibalism. He thought they'd eat that up at MGM. And they did. They

25:55.680 --> 26:03.980
thought it'd be a great idea for a film. So it was bought as a cannibalism film.
And I saw the screenplay, and it was pretty atrocious, and I could not do

26:03.980 --> 26:12.060
anything. By contract, I couldn't change one word. So what I did do, I kept
saying a memo of what was wrong physically, how it could not work. And they made

26:12.060 --> 26:18.880
a lot of changes. I went down the set and pointed out things that hadn't been
done. And I gave copies of the book to all the actors and all the technical

26:18.880 --> 26:29.220
people, and they got very interested. And I talked to Eddie Robinson. I remember
he talked to Dick Fleischer. I heard him say, I don't understand who I'm

26:29.220 --> 26:36.940
supposed to be. What is this role? And there's no way of telling that rotten
screenplay what it was. So I asked if I could talk to him. I introduced myself.

26:37.460 --> 26:46.320
And we had lunch. I said, I wrote the book. Oh, that's very interesting. The
literate man, the art collector, you know. I explained that in the book, in the

26:46.320 --> 26:56.560
year 2000, that is me, my army record, my age. Here or there, not here, the old
man, is the only person who knew the good world. That's his playing. He said,

26:56.760 --> 27:05.960
the only person who lived when the world was green. He said, that's a good idea.
That's not bad. Having got that much, he went away and acted. A lot of that was

27:05.960 --> 27:14.780
created on camera, interfaced between the director and the actors. And I like to
think myself, that I was there all the time. And I like to feel, A, it was my

